<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18440819-2178">
               <interp inst="t18440819-2178" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18440819"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18440819-2178" type="date" value="18440819"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18440819-2178-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2178-18440819 t18440819-2178-offence-1 t18440819-2178-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>2178. <persName id="def1-2178-18440819" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2178-18440819" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2178-18440819" type="age" value="17"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2178-18440819" type="surname" value="BOWERMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2178-18440819" type="given" value="FAITH"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">FAITH BOWERMAN</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18440819-2178-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18440819-2178-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="kill"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18440819-2178-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="infanticide"></interp> for the wilful murder of her female child.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SIMON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1316" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1316" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1316" type="surname" value="BOWERMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1316" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN BOWERMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Joseph Bowerman, the prisoner's brother, and live in Belvidere-road, Lambeth. The prisoner came to reside with us three or four months before the 1st of July—I had no reason to sus<lb></lb>pect that she was in the family way—on the morning of the 1st of July, about half-past eight o'clock I went out for some salts for the prisoner, as she told me she was not very well—I did not recommend her to take medicine—she told me her sister had given it to her when she was ill—I was gone about ten minutes or a quarter of an hour at the outside—I had a key and let myself in—I found the prisoner standing at the foot of the stairs—I observed a great deal of blood in the passage and on the stairs-—I told her 1 thought she had been delivered of a child—she positively denied it and said she had not, that</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184408190203"></xptr>
               <p>it was the regular course of nature—I have a child myself—I advised her to go to bed, but she would not—I went and fetched my husband—I was absent I should say nearly an hour—shortly after my return a policeman came to the house—I saw nothing of any child—I do not know whether she had prepared any linen—there was plenty of mine about.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHARNOCK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I suppose you have not looked about that? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—my child is twelve months old—the prisoner was par<lb></lb>ticularly kind to it, and was a very good girl indeed—I have been married two years.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1317" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1317" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1317" type="surname" value="MOODY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1317" type="given" value="EDWARD JAMES"></interp>EDWARD JAMES MOODY</persName>
                  </hi>. I worked for Mr. Patrick at the time in ques<lb></lb>tion and live in the Waterloo-road. On the morning of the 1st of July, when I was going to work down to my master's yard, I saw something lying just outside the gate of Mr. Patrick's yard—there are two gates, and this was the inner one—it is a wide road—there are two yards within one large gate—the wall of Mr. Bowerman's house runs down by the side of the gate—I did not know what it was, but on going near to it I thought it was a child—I communicated what I had seen to a person named Glaire—I went quite close to it—I thought it was a child—it was naked—it was lying about two yards from the wall.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> What time in the morning was it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> A quarter to nine o'clock—it was two or three yards from the side of the wall, some dis<lb></lb>tance from the wall—this gateway is a private way—it is open for any one that works for Mr. Patrick—not for strangers to pass through—people do not go down there—it does not lead anywhere—it is all open there—there is no covering at all—I should say it is as wide as thit Court—anybody in the main road could see down the road and see what I saw—it was six, seven, or eight yards from the main road—I did not see any other per<lb></lb>son there—there is an outer gate which comes into the Belvidere-road—that is open before six o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1318" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1318" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1318" type="surname" value="GLAIRE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1318" type="given" value="EDMUND"></interp>EDMUND GLAIRE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am one of Mr. Patrick's labourers. On the 1st of July I received a communication from Moody, in consequence of which I went into the roadway leading to my master's premises, and saw a new born female child—I picked it up and put it in my apron—the navel string was exposed, and through that I observed its not being many moments born—on the way to the doctor's I looked at it, and it was foaming at the mouth—I observed a lump on the side of its head, and the shoulder very much dis<lb></lb>figured—I took it to Dr. Carruthers's shop, by the York-road, Lambeth—a policeman was sent for—the child was alive.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1319" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1319" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1319" type="surname" value="COLLISON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1319" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN COLLISON</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable N</hi> 427.) On the 1st of July I saw Glaire go into a doctor's shop—I followed him and saw the cbiwlaid on the table in the doctor's parlour—it was a female new born infant—part of the skull appeared driven in—I took it up to the workhouse—it died about two hours after—I have been to Mr. Bowerman's premises—the yard from the house to the bottom is twenty-eight feet long—the wall is twelve feet high next the house, but the nearest part to where the child was is ten feet inside and six feet three inches without, where the child was lying—I was not present when it was picked up.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1320" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1320" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1320" type="surname" value="HART"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1320" type="given" value="HENRY JAMES"></interp>HENRY JAMES HART</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable L</hi> 58.) On the 1st of July, in con<lb></lb>sequence of information, I went to Mr. Patrick's roadway—I observed some blood on a stone in the road, about three yards from the wall—I looked over the wall, and saw a quantity of blood in the yard—I went round to Mr. Bowerman's door, and knocked—the prisoner opened the door with a child in her arms, which appeared about twelve months old—this was a little after ten o'clock—I asked her if there had been a child born in the yard or in the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184408190204"></xptr>
               <p>house that morning—she said no, it was not her—I asked her if she knew anything of it—she said no, she did not—her apron and hands were covered with blood—I called her attention to that fact—I left a man in charge of the door, and went to the station, and communicated with the inspector on duty—he came back to the house with me—I was sent for a doctor—the prisoner seemed greatly agitated, and very weakly—on a subsequent occasion I ex<lb></lb>amined the premises, and saw an after-birth found in the dust-hole—I saw it put into a basket, and taken to the workhouse by James Brook, <hi rend="italic">L</hi> 118—he is not here.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You say you saw some blood on a stone in Patrick's yard? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> In the gateway of the yard, about the length of this Court from the Belvidere-road—one road leads into another person's road, and Mr. Pa<lb></lb>trick's also—the stone was right in the middle of the gateway, about twelve yards out of the Belvidere-road, I should think—I did not measure it—the after-birth was found during the time the doctor was in the parlour, about ten o'clock the same morning—I saw it found—the dust-hole is about three yards from the kitchen—the stone I saw with the blood on was about three yards from the wall—I did not measure it—it appeared to be a piece of paving-stone, lying in the ground.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MRS. BOWERMAN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> When I went out that morning, I left no one in the house but the prisoner and my baby, no servant.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1321" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1321" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1321" type="surname" value="DUKE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1321" type="given" value="OLIVER"></interp>OLIVER DUKE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the surgeon of Lambeth workhouse. On the 1st of July a messenger from the workhouse came to fetch me—I went, and saw the child—it was in the possession of a nurse—the head appeared very much contused, the bones of the skull appeared fractured, and the back of the child was bruised very much—it lived about two hours after I saw it—an after-birth was also produced to me, I think by Hart—in my judgment, the bruise on the head caused the death—the other bruises were not of a very serious nature.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Do you know the age of the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I believe she is about nineteen—the head is the first part that makes its appearance in the world, in a confinement—I should think the bruises were not such as would arise from the child striking its head against the stairs, if suspended from the mother—striking the head against the stairs, or any hard substance, would produce the appearances I saw—the loss of blood, if the mother deli<lb></lb>vered herself, would very much affect her mind—it might affect the brain, so as to produce almost frenzy—I should say a mother so young as seventeen or eighteen would have great difficulty in delivering herself—it is very doubtful how long it would take for a girl of her age to deliver herself, it depends on the obstacles met with—supposing the pains of labour had not come on, I should think it would be impossible for a person to be delivered under some hours—I cannot say—I examined the person of the prisoner when she came into the hospital, about two hours after I had seen the child—there were symptoms of her having been delivered.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18440819-2178-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18440819-2178-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18440819-2178-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="manslaughter"></interp>
                     <hi rend="smallCaps">GUILTY</hi> 
                     <hi rend="italic">of Manslaughter.</hi>
                  </rs> Aged 17.—<hi rend="italic">
                     <rs id="t18440819-2178-punishment-242" type="punishmentDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-2178-punishment-242" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
